WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.040
Thank you.

00:00:08.040 --> 00:00:13.420
Today I'm going to talk about running Shiny without a server, but before I get there,

00:00:13.420 --> 00:00:17.240
it's come to my attention that some people in our community might not know what a server

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:20.160
even is, and that's totally okay.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:25.059
A server is a computer that's running 24-7, connected to the Internet, and it stands ready

00:00:25.059 --> 00:00:28.680
at all times to serve up your Shiny app using R or Python.

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:31.639
Which makes sense, our apps are written in R or Python.

00:00:31.639 --> 00:00:36.279
So if you want to share your Shiny app with other people, you need a server.

00:00:36.279 --> 00:00:39.599
It is a requirement, and it has to be running R or Python.

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:44.520
And that server can take many shapes and sizes, this is a Raspberry Pi, that is a totally

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:48.880
cromulent server, and you could have servers like this.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:52.000
Those are actually buildings in Toronto, but they kind of look like servers, so I was like

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.240
sure.

00:00:55.240 --> 00:01:02.520
And Posit and other places in the Shiny community make it pretty easy, actually, to get your

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:03.520
app onto a server.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:06.800
You might not even know that there's a server on the other side.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.360
And we have stuff for the cloud, we have stuff for on-prem, we have stuff that's free, we

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:16.120
have stuff that's enterprise-priced, and they all do a great job at the different things

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:18.239
that they do.

00:01:18.239 --> 00:01:19.599
But they all have trade-offs, right?

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:25.239
They all have different pros and cons, and different trade-offs between cost, scalability,

00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:27.720
and features.

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:36.559
And this is especially annoying to academics, I think, when there are maybe pretty severe

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:39.559
resource constraints on what's available to them, and yet there are things that they want

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:41.019
to express with Shiny.

00:01:41.019 --> 00:01:45.720
And not just academics, but I'm going to pick on them, because I think I hear it a lot from

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:47.019
them.

00:01:47.019 --> 00:01:51.980
And what they hate is this, that the cost is proportional to the amount of computational

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:55.019
complexity in your app, and the number of users.

00:01:55.019 --> 00:02:01.620
So that might have nothing to do with how much money they have available, but it's something

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:04.019
that is a reality for them nonetheless.

00:02:04.019 --> 00:02:10.380
So I think for a lot of academics I talk to especially, but also some hobbyists and freelancers,

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:17.660
their attitude is like this, wouldn't it be easier if it all just blew away?

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:21.419
And for a long time, that was a total pipe dream.

00:02:21.419 --> 00:02:27.860
But a few years ago, I started to hear rumblings about this thing called WebAssembly, or Wasm.

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:32.539
And I'm going to give you the shortest description of Wasm that I can.

00:02:32.539 --> 00:02:33.699
What is Wasm?

00:02:33.699 --> 00:02:37.339
Well, before Wasm, there was just JavaScript.

00:02:37.339 --> 00:02:41.220
The browser only spoke one programming language, and it was JavaScript.

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:43.220
And it didn't matter how you felt about JavaScript.

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:47.699
If you wanted to target the browser, that was the language you had to write in.

00:02:47.699 --> 00:02:50.460
And nowadays, browsers speak two languages.

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:53.580
There's still JavaScript, and now there's this new thing called Wasm.

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:59.460
But they are different because Wasm was designed for humans to write, and Wasm is designed

00:02:59.460 --> 00:03:01.619
for compilers to emit.

00:03:01.619 --> 00:03:04.259
So you don't write Wasm as a human being.

00:03:04.259 --> 00:03:06.740
You write code in something like C or C++.

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:12.500
You compile it to Wasm, and that Wasm then runs in the browser.

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:16.059
Now let's talk about why this is exciting.

00:03:16.059 --> 00:03:22.660
And before we can, I have to come clean and admit to you all that I was wrong about Wasm,

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:27.300
that I was a huge skeptic of all this, and I'm going to explain why.

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:33.419
And a lot of people within the company and some people outside of the company would hear

00:03:33.419 --> 00:03:38.580
about Wasm, however they hear about things, and come to me or come to our team and say,

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:40.059
I have this great idea.

00:03:40.059 --> 00:03:43.020
I have had this breakthrough in reasoning.

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:47.500
Shiny is written in R. R is written in C++.

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:50.100
C++ can be compiled to Wasm.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:54.100
Therefore, Shiny can be compiled to Wasm QED.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:57.259
Let me know when it ships.

00:03:57.259 --> 00:04:02.339
And this is a chain of reasoning that occurred independently to multiple people over multiple

00:04:02.339 --> 00:04:09.380
years, and each time we would have this discussion, and I would have to disappoint them, and my

00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:16.579
response eventually was like, well, actually, let me school you on what's happening here.

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:21.179
Compiling C and C++ to Wasm is just the tip of a gigantic iceberg.

00:04:21.179 --> 00:04:25.500
This is the biggest iceberg I could find on Unsplash, but if I could make the top smaller

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.220
and the bottom bigger, I would.

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:33.700
Because compiling C and C++ to Wasm is very exciting, but if you think about what R does

00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:38.500
and what Python does, there's all this stuff under the surface beyond just interpreting

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:41.339
C and C++ instructions.

00:04:41.339 --> 00:04:47.660
There are all these things that are either from the operating system or from libraries

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:54.220
that we've built on over the years, and they are not available in Wasm.

00:04:54.220 --> 00:04:58.940
And it's not just a matter of rebuilding those pieces that are missing, because the

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:03.980
environment that Wasm runs in is the browser, and the browser has a number of limitations

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:07.299
that your desktop computer is not subject to.

00:05:07.299 --> 00:05:11.140
In the browser, you cannot launch a process, you can't open a network connection, you can't

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:17.119
even perform I.O., like reading from a disk or fetching from the network, synchronously.

00:05:17.119 --> 00:05:21.940
You can't handle something as simple as Control-C.

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:28.500
And Wasm does not lift any of these restrictions in and of itself, instead, it really just

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:32.600
makes it hurt more, because we have this software already written that's expecting to be able

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:36.619
to do these things, and we really wanted to just make it run in the browser, and we cannot

00:05:36.619 --> 00:05:40.839
because these things make it so hard.

00:05:40.839 --> 00:05:47.619
And it makes me think of this Haitian proverb, de yin wan, yin wan, and what that means is

00:05:47.619 --> 00:05:51.500
beyond mountains, more mountains.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:55.420
Whatever hill you have to climb, whatever obstacle you're facing, whatever challenge

00:05:55.420 --> 00:06:03.739
you overcome, when you get to the other side, it's just more of the same.

00:06:03.739 --> 00:06:10.380
And lucky for me, lucky for you, lucky for all of us, not everybody thought like I did.

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:13.619
Not everybody had the same reaction that I did to these challenges.

00:06:13.619 --> 00:06:16.019
Because I got to the point where I was getting pretty frustrated.

00:06:16.019 --> 00:06:21.260
I was like, stop suggesting we port things to Wasm, stop trying to make Wasm happen,

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:24.459
it's not going to happen.

00:06:24.459 --> 00:06:31.100
And there are some people that are wired very differently than me that did some pretty amazing

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:32.100
things.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:37.579
Alon Zakai showed up one day on the internet and said, hi, I built a compiler tool chain

00:06:37.579 --> 00:06:40.859
and computing platform that runs on Wasm, that's called Emscripten.

00:06:40.859 --> 00:06:44.660
And this thing is, as far as I'm concerned, it's magic.

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:51.779
This is replacing both the GCC tool chain and big parts of Linux and making them available

00:06:51.779 --> 00:06:52.779
in the browser.

00:06:52.779 --> 00:06:56.339
And if that doesn't mean anything to you, all the more reason you should be grateful

00:06:56.339 --> 00:06:59.059
that he's doing this work.

00:06:59.059 --> 00:07:03.299
Michael Trotboom, who is a complete legend in the Python space, and just one more reason

00:07:03.299 --> 00:07:07.899
why he's a legend, just put out a blog post one day saying, oh, you know, I was curious

00:07:07.899 --> 00:07:08.899
if it was possible.

00:07:08.899 --> 00:07:13.220
So I patched NumPy, Matplotlib, and Pandas, the whole scientific Python stack now runs

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:17.779
in the browser, that's called PyDyed.

00:07:17.779 --> 00:07:23.459
And Winston Chang on my team, over a weekend, did a little bit of hacking, literally over

00:07:23.459 --> 00:07:24.459
a weekend.

00:07:24.459 --> 00:07:25.459
Okay.

00:07:25.459 --> 00:07:30.859
Yeah, I was gone.

00:07:30.859 --> 00:07:38.019
And apparently what happens when I'm gone is people do things I ask them not to.

00:07:38.019 --> 00:07:42.260
And Winston showed up one day and said, hey, I made Shiny run on PyDyed and that became

00:07:42.299 --> 00:07:45.299
Shiny live.

00:07:45.299 --> 00:07:50.940
And our own George Stagg and Lionel Henry came up with, well, George Stagg, even before

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:57.019
he worked for Posit, I think because he was frustrated that a class that he was teaching,

00:07:57.019 --> 00:08:01.299
like he didn't want to stand up a server, went and instead did this miraculous thing

00:08:01.299 --> 00:08:07.459
and created WebR.

00:08:07.459 --> 00:08:10.799
And it was interesting, in putting together this talk, I actually learned a little bit

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:20.040
more about this saying that in Haiti, it has really not just a negative meaning, that

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:26.320
it is a meaning that's about, yes, a grim situation, which Haiti, more than almost any

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:32.320
other country, finds itself in perpetually, but there is also sort of a resilience to

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:33.320
it.

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:38.799
This acknowledgment that whatever problems we face, we will always face more problems

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:43.159
And that doesn't stop us from getting up and doing what needs to be done.

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:49.000
And in that way, it's the same mountains that they're looking at, that people like George

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.799
and Winston and all the other people who have contributed to this Wiles and Stagg saw the

00:08:54.799 --> 00:08:59.440
same mountains, but instead of concluding, well, the challenges will never end, so let's

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:04.119
not begin the journey, instead they just decided, well, let's see how far we can go.

00:09:04.119 --> 00:09:07.400
And it turns out that even though there are more mountains in the distance from where

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:11.239
we are today, we have come in an awful long way.

00:09:11.239 --> 00:09:16.640
So this time last year, we had the pleasure to introduce Shiny Live for Python, and that

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:18.460
was super fun.

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:22.679
This basically moves this model that I talked about in the beginning where you have a server

00:09:22.679 --> 00:09:27.479
that's running Python, and it flips it on its head so that the server is running essentially

00:09:27.479 --> 00:09:28.479
nothing.

00:09:28.479 --> 00:09:35.440
The server just serves up HTML and JavaScript, and Python runs inside of the browser for

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:38.239
everybody who connects.

00:09:38.239 --> 00:09:43.159
And I am very pleased to tell you that our estimate from last year, that it would be

00:09:43.159 --> 00:09:48.599
a couple of years before we had this for R, did not take into account George Stagg, and

00:09:48.599 --> 00:09:55.479
today, Shiny Live for R is available.

00:09:55.479 --> 00:10:06.559
It feels incredible to stand up here and take credit for work I had no part in.

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:11.479
So how to use Shiny Live, and this is actually pretty interesting because everything from

00:10:11.479 --> 00:10:14.400
here on out applies equally to R and Python.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:16.200
There's very little difference between these two.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:20.599
So let's talk about how we use Shiny Live, and there are actually three different options

00:10:20.599 --> 00:10:23.119
that are available.

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:27.320
You can convert, you can fiddle, and you can include, and I will go through each of those

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:29.960
in turn.

00:10:29.960 --> 00:10:31.960
The first option is to convert.

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:38.760
So you take your app.R, any other code files you have, any data files you want, and you

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:45.000
pass them into this simple Shiny Live export function, and that will take your app directory

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:49.119
and turn it into a completely static set of assets.

00:10:49.119 --> 00:10:53.799
You can then take that and upload it to GitHub Pages, for example.

00:10:53.799 --> 00:11:00.599
This entire presentation is uploaded to, well, you'll see it in a second.

00:11:00.599 --> 00:11:06.039
And this exact same workflow also applies to Python, except instead of installing the

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:12.380
R Shiny Live package, you just pip install Shiny Live, and it's the same deal.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:16.520
So this is a great option if you want to take your Shiny application and turn it into a

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:19.640
standalone website.

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:27.280
Now one just unfortunate wrinkle about this is that due to sort of browser security rules,

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:32.719
you cannot simply double-click the HTML file that is sitting in this directory when you're

00:11:32.719 --> 00:11:34.880
testing on your own machine.

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:40.080
The browser will not let certain advanced browser features be used unless it sees that

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:44.039
the URL bar has an HTTP in it.

00:11:44.039 --> 00:11:48.200
Or if you are using Shiny for R, you would run this HTTPUV command.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:54.239
If you're running Shiny for Python, you would run that line three Python HTTP.server command.

00:11:54.239 --> 00:12:02.119
If you are uploading your static Shiny app to a web server, then none of this matters,

00:12:02.119 --> 00:12:03.719
none of this applies.

00:12:03.719 --> 00:12:04.719
Okay.

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:05.840
Details, details.

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:08.280
Option number two is Fiddle.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:10.859
So we have a website called ShinyLive.io.

00:12:10.859 --> 00:12:15.739
How many of you have taken a look at ShinyLive.io for Shiny for Python over the last year?

00:12:15.739 --> 00:12:16.739
Okay.

00:12:16.739 --> 00:12:17.739
Great.

00:12:17.739 --> 00:12:18.739
So quite a few.

00:12:18.739 --> 00:12:22.219
And this is a way that you can write and share Shiny apps directly in the browser.

00:12:22.219 --> 00:12:26.020
No need to install R or Python on your local machine.

00:12:26.020 --> 00:12:27.020
And it looks like this.

00:12:27.020 --> 00:12:30.260
You have an editor that you can write code in.

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:35.739
And when you hit the play button, it generates the view on the right, and you can fully use

00:12:35.739 --> 00:12:36.739
that.

00:12:36.739 --> 00:12:37.739
That's a Shiny app.

00:12:37.739 --> 00:12:41.059
It's crazy to me that this works, but it somehow does work.

00:12:41.059 --> 00:12:46.739
That is running Python inside of your browser, and you get a full Shiny app.

00:12:46.739 --> 00:12:49.940
Shiny for Python and Shiny for R have different links.

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:51.919
I will repeat these links at the end.

00:12:51.919 --> 00:12:55.900
But just so you know, you cannot go to the you cannot currently go to the Python side

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:57.780
and find a link to the R side or vice versa.

00:12:57.780 --> 00:13:02.539
You just have to know the right URL.

00:13:02.539 --> 00:13:07.119
ShinyLive.io, you can view and run examples that we have created, and you can also create

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:09.159
your own apps from scratch.

00:13:09.159 --> 00:13:13.719
You can also share apps that you create via URL to your, well, to anyone.

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:18.159
And you can save apps to GitHub Gists if you want.

00:13:18.159 --> 00:13:19.760
Okay.

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:24.000
Maybe the most exciting one is option three.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.520
Option three, we have a Shiny Live Cordo extension.

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:34.599
So you can take your Cordo documents and insert these Shiny Live-R flavored chunks and put

00:13:34.599 --> 00:13:36.880
a full-on Shiny app in there.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:41.739
And it is now just when you render it to HTML, you have a Shiny app that just works inside

00:13:41.739 --> 00:13:45.960
of your HTML.

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:49.400
Yeah.

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:54.679
So, this is an example.

00:13:54.679 --> 00:13:56.559
Actually, this came up yesterday.

00:13:56.559 --> 00:14:03.159
I had lunch next to Erin Howard of Oregon State University.

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:09.840
She mentioned this Central Limit Theorem app that she had built that really helped in getting

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.280
the idea of the Central Limit Theorem across.

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:14.280
This is not her app.

00:14:14.280 --> 00:14:18.440
I'm sure hers was better, but I wrote this in the middle of the night last night.

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:22.599
And you can see here that this is fully running.

00:14:22.599 --> 00:14:23.840
It's a Shiny app.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:25.479
This is a Cordo document.

00:14:25.479 --> 00:14:28.020
There's no server behind it.

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:34.140
So for this app, it's drawing a bunch of samples from a normal distribution.

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:38.380
And because it's only 100 samples, that blue line is sort of jumping around the red, which

