is the true mean.

00:14:40.020 --> 00:14:41.539
And if I increase that number...

00:14:41.539 --> 00:14:46.820
Oh, sorry.

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:49.419
I'm on the wrong screen.

00:14:49.419 --> 00:14:54.580
Yeah, you can see that you...

00:14:54.580 --> 00:14:55.580
Well, you get the idea.

00:14:55.580 --> 00:15:03.299
I don't need to tell you guys how it works.

00:15:03.299 --> 00:15:08.340
That's great to see how many Central Limit Theorem fans are in the audience.

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:15.159
Which brings me to another point that usually in technology, something gets cheaper, great.

00:15:15.159 --> 00:15:18.419
We can do that thing for less money.

00:15:18.419 --> 00:15:22.299
But sometimes when the price drops enough, you're not just doing the same thing that

00:15:22.299 --> 00:15:24.799
you were doing before for less money.

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:26.440
You can do entirely new things.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:28.880
And let me give an example.

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:30.780
This is a mainframe computer.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:32.820
This is the 60s.

00:15:32.820 --> 00:15:40.159
That cost millions of dollars, and it was used for weather research or military research.

00:15:40.159 --> 00:15:42.440
In the 70s, we had mini computers.

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:46.640
These were hundreds of thousands of dollars, and maybe medium to large-sized businesses

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:52.080
would use these to run their accounting software.

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:57.159
In the 80s, we had PCs that cost thousands of dollars, and you might write a term paper

00:15:57.159 --> 00:16:03.359
on this or do your taxes or play a game.

00:16:03.359 --> 00:16:07.179
Today we have these magical devices that cost hundreds of dollars, and we use them to check

00:16:07.179 --> 00:16:13.419
our YouTube channel subscriber count while we're having a latte.

00:16:13.419 --> 00:16:17.440
And recently, we even have these computing devices that cost tens of dollars, and they

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:21.880
exist only for the purpose of helping you find your keys.

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:26.320
So as the price drops, the scenarios drastically change.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:31.760
What computers were good for and what computers are good for now are entirely different, and

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:38.919
that never would have happened without that drastic decrease in price.

00:16:38.919 --> 00:16:44.020
And that's what we found – well, that's what I found maybe most surprising once I

00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:48.919
got over the initial shock that this stuff works at all, was that this is not just about

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:53.080
taking the kinds of apps that we already write with Shiny, the things that Shiny was already

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:57.039
good at, and making them cheaper than before.

00:16:57.039 --> 00:17:02.239
We very quickly were finding new ways to use Shiny that would not have been possible before.

00:17:02.239 --> 00:17:11.119
And one is our Shiny for Python tutorial has these embedded Shiny app editors bundled throughout

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:13.560
our website, throughout our tutorial.

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:18.239
And this lets you, as someone who's learning Shiny for Python, interact with the code,

00:17:18.239 --> 00:17:21.000
try different things, and then hit the play button and immediately see what happens.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:26.400
And you can do all this without needing to install Python or Shiny on your machine.

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:31.420
And this is not something that we had attempted before.

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:35.000
And we extended that concept also to our examples.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.760
Our Shiny for Python website uses a Cordodoc package, and that package works very nicely

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:43.099
with Shiny Live for Python.

00:17:43.099 --> 00:17:47.199
So all of our examples, especially the ones that have anything to do with UI, we can have

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:52.439
running examples that will actually instantiate a new Shiny app inside the browser and show

00:17:52.439 --> 00:17:56.800
you exactly what happens.

00:17:56.800 --> 00:18:00.400
This doesn't work yet, but you could certainly imagine that package downsites for R in general

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:03.199
could do this sort of thing.

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:04.359
This is the GT package.

00:18:04.359 --> 00:18:10.400
It's an incredibly beautiful package for creating tables, and you could, yeah, I'd be excited

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:16.119
about GT's documentation having Shiny apps that help you understand what the different

00:18:16.119 --> 00:18:19.400
options do.

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:24.640
And there is a group from the R Consortium that's working with the FDA that are trying

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:31.439
to take WebR and Shiny Live and see if they can use that to help accelerate clinical study

00:18:31.439 --> 00:18:40.579
reporting by bundling Shiny apps with their clinical trial submissions.

00:18:40.579 --> 00:18:47.300
And this is where I want to turn it over to you and ask, what possibilities can you

00:18:47.300 --> 00:18:51.739
find in your work to take advantage of these new possibilities for Shiny?

00:18:51.739 --> 00:18:55.859
Could your next presentation be more compelling with a little Shiny?

00:18:55.859 --> 00:18:59.819
Could your lecture notes lead to deeper understanding?

00:18:59.819 --> 00:19:02.819
Can your blog posts be more powerful?

00:19:02.819 --> 00:19:06.420
Or maybe you just want to bewilder your students with a random game of Hangman in the middle

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:08.660
of their homework.

00:19:08.660 --> 00:19:15.339
That comment is inspired by Chelsea Parlette-Pellariti, who wrote one of these.

00:19:15.339 --> 00:19:21.459
I'm not sure why, but you can click on the link and play Hangman in your browser.

00:19:21.459 --> 00:19:28.339
So to recap, there are these three ways to use it, convert, fiddle, and include.

00:19:28.339 --> 00:19:32.040
Now with my last 30 seconds, there are limitations.

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:35.859
I wasn't wrong that this is a challenging computing environment to try to do data science

00:19:35.859 --> 00:19:37.599
in.

00:19:37.599 --> 00:19:41.199
Probably the most obvious is that the slower start time and larger download size, because

00:19:41.199 --> 00:19:47.040
you are downloading your data, Python, any packages you need, or R if it's R, you're

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:49.719
downloading all of those to your machine.

00:19:49.719 --> 00:19:52.959
It's really bad for R right now, but over the next couple of weeks, it'll be better.

00:19:52.959 --> 00:19:54.959
And some things are just not going to work.

00:19:54.959 --> 00:20:01.560
So the native Shiny execution model is not going away, but now we also have Shiny Live.

00:20:01.560 --> 00:20:02.560
Thank you.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:03.560
Thank you.

00:20:03.560 --> 00:20:04.560
Thank you.

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:05.560
Thank you.

